text: All right, Ima take a crack at this film. Grab a snack if you're interested in reading a lot of text. And yes, I'm completely aware of the idea of simply waiting for the movie to come out, but I look at doing this as a way to save money based on watching trailers alone. And yes, this comment is EXTREMELY long, so its up to you to continue reading.  Takes place present day. Music and style feels 80s, but cellphones are seen throughout, so definitely after the events of the first film which took place in South Carolina. A family of four decide to stay at a seemingly dilapidated trailer park near Gaglin Lake in Florida to visit family, and find nothing out of the ordinary about it being COMPLETELY empty. "I think everybody leaves after Labor Day" the mom says. Okay, sure, but where are the family members you came to visit? And you're going to gloss over the fact there's food already in the fridge of the house that is supposed to be vacant? So the Strangers murdered EVERYONE in the trailer park before this family's arrival, their bodies will possibly be discovered throughout, and its just pure coincidence of this family's arrival.   So, somehow the father and son get separated from the mother and daughter. They probably go out to check the rest of the park to figure out the deal of the Dollface girl and see if there's anyone else there. Dollface comes back and traps mother and daughter in bathroom. Daughter gets out through sunroof while the Mom either gets brutally murdered, or disappears. Father, son and daughter hideout in another abandoned trailer home, where father finds revolver to attack Strangers. A cop, who comes by to check out the place every now and then, shows up to find it deserted, and the Dad will accidentally kill the cop. So the Dad goes outside with gun to get to cop's car and/or deal with Strangers, either to get brutally murdered, or disappear.  Man in Mask crashes truck through home, forcing brother and sister to run and hide out.  Brother distracts Man in Mask to follow him to pool while sister hides in tunnel. Brother stabs the Man in Mask at pool,  but either gets brutally murdered or disappears. Pin Up Girl and Dollface, meanwhile, find sister in tunnel and force her out. Sister hides in police car, but Man in Mask, not dead from stab wound, comes back with truck and rams into it repeatedly to force her out, and causes an explosion. The Man in Mask, still in truck that is now on fire, continues to advance towards the bloodied Sister.   Now, the conclusion. Either A) Family gets murdered one by one until the sister is left to fend for herself, and she either lives or dies while the Strangers continue on to kill another day. Or B) the Sister is knocked unconscious, and wakes up to a scene similar to the first film, where her and her family are one by one brutally murdered by the Strangers. Either way, most of the family wind up dead, but the film might have a cheap mid-credit scene with Liv Tyler from the first one coming in back in hopes to get funding for a third in which she gets revenge.

text: Just wanted to convey the primary issue with this sequel. They're continuing the lore of the first one, where the killers won, and murdered everyone. Clearly, based upon the constraints of said lore, the killers cannot fail; the story will not allow it. As such, it's pretty damn clear how this movie ends, and that is reason enough to not watch it, let alone have any need to watch it.  Furthermore, this movie is mudding the general lore too much. The first one had a proper atmosphere, two people trapped in a house. This one introduces two children, but that convolutes the solidarity of the atmosphere.  I'm just not impressed.

It still remains one of the most intense horror movies I have ever seen. The great thing about the first was the randomness of the crime and how they just stab them and walk away. I really like the writer for part 2, so I will stay optimistic. It's directed by two people, and the most recent thing they did is 47 meters down. My fingers are crossed, but I'm not getting my hopes up. The trailer was interesting, though.

text: They need to combine a horror movie like this with an realistic action movie, you know where the responding cops aren‚Äôt made out to be bumbling idiots or where these scumbags choose the wrong houses. Maybe a house full of armed law-abiding citizens, where the husband is a military vet armed with a Sig Sauer P226 and AR-15. You know, where the good guys/intended victims wipes out the murderers.   It‚Äôd certainly be a fresh idea for a movie instead of the same ole regurgitated crap where some serial killers target an innocent family, go out of the way to theatrically taunt their intended victims prior to murdering them only to get away with it - and usually all with no explanation. It‚Äôs the same old story line in virtually every horror movie.  Of course if they did, I suppose the movie wouldn‚Äôt last all that long or unfortunately the writers would just make the citizens out to be bumbling idiots the same way they always do with the cops in order to make it possible for the murdering scumbags to prevail. Hollywood is running out of fresh, original ideas. Making movies that embrace the principles of individual liberty would certainly be nice though, or at least doing sometime different instead of this same washed up crap that pushes death culture or political correctness.

text: Spoilers:  While I enjoyed this movie, there were many dumb decisions made by the main characters that had me yelling at the screen, like in most horrors, but moreso with this one. The first thing: why in the flying holy motherfuck would the father and son leave their wife/mother and daughter/sister in the house all alone while they go back to the house to view their dead uncle/aunt- makes no sense. 2nd dumb thing, why have the son leave the dieing dad in the car for the male attacker to come back and finish him off?! Why not have the son just shoot the dad and end his misery?! 3rd dumb thing, why didn't the son shoot that masked female attacker. That said, this movie, like the original still was scary and gory, try watching it at night alone or at night in the theater! I also loved the stalking scenes, but there were so many problems with this one, and the eery music from the first one wasn't here either. 6/10 C.

Many comments here indicate that not knowing the motive of the killers bugs them but that is the whole point of the movie and I found it beautiful it is made this way as it‚Äôs also loosely based on a real event. I enjoyed watching the movie. The cinematography and music as well as sound choices are great. Perhaps the only things that bothered me were the overly-used F words and ‚ÄúLeave us alone‚Äù phrase but come on, who would in the right mind scream different things when they‚Äôre about to die? And of course there are comments on why shouldn‚Äôt one of the characters just shoot away. The answer is simple. Fight or flight. Science would perhaps shed some light. Also Kinsey‚Äôs acting was quite basic, while the rest was excellent - Luke‚Äôs being the best. Overall, 8/10. That‚Äôs an A. A good movie to try out with your friends.

text: --- SPOILERS --- Wow that is the stupidest family I have ever witnessed. This movie is riddled with silly mistakes and inaccuracies. Their lives are at stake, so let's not grab a weapon of any sort. Because why protect yourself? Even with a lamp or frying pan, an object that can kill someone if used enough and correctly. Oh and my windshield got smashed while cruising at 30 mph, better accelerate into a double wide. Plus, a shotgun blast to the chest at 3 feet definitely doesn't kill someone. Ya, also lets not go to the side of vehicles that are trying to run us over... because trucks can definitely drive sideways. Speaking of trucks, why is a 1975 Ford pickup invincible? After all the ramming of the SUV, which is enough to kill the truck because older vehicles are terrible in crash ratings and impacts, but the explosion would certainly melt the rubber distributor cap and spark plug wires immediately, causing the truck to die in 2 seconds. That's just a few of a hundred idiotic aspects of this silly film.

text: "Based on true events" is a vague statement. It can mean that one character is based on a real person, or that the historical time period in which the movie takes place actually happened, or it can mean that the movie is more or less a biopic. And the difference between based on true events and based on a true story is that, if a movie says based on true events, it is usually a bunch of little stories and things that have been said that are all put together into one coherent story. ... Based on a true story usually means something like a biopic.
